Local install (Linux)
# on systems with package or from repo - often installed via package manager or download from hashcat.net
sudo apt install -y hashcat

Basic wordlist attack (Hashcat)
# example for MD5 (hash mode 0). Adjust -m for hash type.
hashcat -m 0 -a 0 sample_hashes/hashes.txt /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt --potfile-path results/hashcat.pot --outfile-format=2 -o results/hashcat_cracked.txt
# show results (hashcat --show)
hashcat --show -m 0 sample_hashes/hashes.txt --potfile-path results/hashcat.pot > results/hashcat_cracked.txt

Docker (if no GPU)
docker run --rm -it -v $(pwd)/sample_hashes:/data -v $(pwd)/results:/results hashcat/hashcat:latest \
hashcat -m 0 -a 0 /data/hashes.txt /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt --potfile-path /results/hashcat.pot -o /results/hashcat_cracked.txt

4) Wordlists & rules

Use curated wordlists (rockyou.txt, custom lists). Small labs: you can create short lists: echo -e "password\n123456\nletmein" > sample_hashes/mylist.txt.

Use rules to mutate wordlists (--rules on John, -r rules/best64.rule on Hashcat).

5) Results & sanitization

Save only cracked username:password pairs or hashed:plaintext in results/. Do NOT commit raw hash dumps containing PII.

Include sample command output snippets and the final results/*.txt in the lab report.




chmod +x TASK3-Password-Cracking/john_run.sh

